div.cell {
  /* Old browsers */
  display: -webkit-box;
  -webkit-box-orient: vertical;
  -webkit-box-align: stretch;
  display: -moz-box;
  -moz-box-orient: vertical;
  -moz-box-align: stretch;
  display: box;
  box-orient: vertical;
  box-align: stretch;
  /* Modern browsers */
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  align-items: stretch;
  border-radius: 2px;
  box-sizing: border-box;
  -moz-box-sizing: border-box;
  -webkit-box-sizing: border-box;
  border-width: 1px;
  border-style: solid;
  border-color: transparent;
  width: 100%;
  padding: 5px;
  /* This acts as a spacer between cells, that is outside the border */
  margin: 0px;
  outline: none;
  position: relative;
  overflow: visible;
}
div.cell:before {
  position: absolute;
  display: block;
  top: -1px;
  left: -1px;
  width: 5px;
  height: calc(100% +  2px);
  content: '';
  background: transparent;
}
div.cell.jupyter-soft-selected {
  border-left-color: #E3F2FD;
  border-left-width: 1px;
  padding-left: 5px;
  border-right-color: #E3F2FD;
  border-right-width: 1px;
  background: #E3F2FD;
}
@media print {
  div.cell.jupyter-soft-selected {
    border-color: transparent;
  }
}
div.cell.selected,
div.cell.selected.jupyter-soft-selected {
  border-color: #ababab;
}
div.cell.selected:before,
div.cell.selected.jupyter-soft-selected:before {
  position: absolute;
  display: block;
  top: -1px;
  left: -1px;
  width: 5px;
  height: calc(100% +  2px);
  content: '';
  background: #42A5F5;
}
@media print {
  div.cell.selected,
  div.cell.selected.jupyter-soft-selected {
    border-color: transparent;
  }
}
.edit_mode div.cell.selected {
  border-color: #66BB6A;
}
.edit_mode div.cell.selected:before {
  position: absolute;

}

  }
}
.prompt {
  /* This needs to be wide enough for 3 digit prompt numbers: In[100]: */
  min-width: 14ex;
  /* This padding is tuned to match the padding on the CodeMirror editor. */
  padding: 0.4em;
  margin: 0px;
  font-family: monospace;
  text-align: right;
  /* This has to match that of the the CodeMirror class line-height below */
  line-height: 1.21429em;
  /* Don't highlight prompt number selection */
  -webkit-touch-callout: none;
  -webkit-user-select: none;
  -khtml-user-select: none;
  -moz-user-select: none;
  -ms-user-select: none;
  user-select: none;
  /* Use default cursor */
  cursor: default;
}
@media (max-width: 540px) {
  .prompt {
    text-align: left;
  }
}
div.inner_cell {
  min-width: 0;
  /* Old browsers */
  display: -webkit-box;
  -webkit-box-orient: vertical;
  -webkit-box-align: stretch;
  display: -moz-box;
  -moz-box-orient: vertical;
  -moz-box-align: stretch;
  display: box;
  box-orient: vertical;
  box-align: stretch;
  /* Modern browsers */
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  align-items: stretch;
  /* Old browsers */
  -webkit-box-flex: 1;
  -moz-box-flex: 1;
  box-flex: 1;
  /* Modern browsers */
  flex: 1;
}
/* input_area and input_prompt must match in top border and margin for alignment */
div.input_area {
  border: 1px solid #cfcfcf;
  border-radius: 2px;
  background: #f7f7f7;
  line-height: 1.21429em;
}
/* This is needed so that empty prompt areas can collapse to zero height when there
   is no content in the output_subarea and the prompt. The main purpose of this is
   to make sure that empty JavaScript output_subareas have no height. */
div.prompt:empty {
  padding-top: 0;
  padding-bottom: 0;
}
div.unrecognized_cell {
  padding: 5px 5px 5px 0px;
  /* Old browsers */
  display: -webkit-box;
  -webkit-box-orient: horizontal;
  -webkit-box-align: stretch;
  display: -moz-box;

}
div.unrecognized_cell .inner_cell {

div.unrecognized_cell .inner_cell a {

div.input_prompt {

}

}

}
/* The following gets added to the <head> if it is detected that the user has a
 * monospace font with inconsistent normal/bold/italic height.  See
 * notebookmain.js.  Such fonts will have keywords vertically offset with
 * respect to the rest of the text.  The user should select a better font.
 * See: https://github.com/ipython/ipython/issues/1503
 *
 * .CodeMirror span {
 *      vertical-align: bottom;
 * }
 */
.CodeMirror {
  line-height: 1.21429em;
  /* Changed from 1em to our global default */
  font-size: 14px;
  height: auto;
  /* Changed to auto to autogrow */
  background: none;
  /* Changed from white to allow our bg to show through */
}
.CodeMirror-scroll {
  /*  The CodeMirror docs are a bit fuzzy on if overflow-y should be hidden or visible.*/
  /*  We have found that if it is visible, vertical scrollbars appear with font size changes.*/
  overflow-y: hidden;
  overflow-x: auto;
}
.CodeMirror-lines {
  /* In CM2, this used to be 0.4em, but in CM3 it went to 4px. We need the em value because */
  /* we have set a different line-height and want this to scale with that. */
  /* Note that this should set vertical padding only, since CodeMirror assumes
       that horizontal padding will be set on CodeMirror pre */
  padding: 0.4em 0;
}
.CodeMirror-linenumber {
  padding: 0 8px 0 4px;
}
.CodeMirror-gutters {
  border-bottom-left-radius: 2px;
  border-top-left-radius: 2px;
}
.CodeMirror pre {
  /* In CM3 this went to 4px from 0 in CM2. This sets horizontal padding only,
    use .CodeMirror-lines for vertical */
  padding: 0 0.4em;
  border: 0;
  border-radius: 0;
}
.CodeMirror-cursor {
  border-left: 1.4px solid black;
}
@media screen and (min-width: 2138px) and (max-width: 4319px) {
  .CodeMirror-cursor {
    border-left: 2px solid black;
  }
}
@media screen and (min-width: 4320px) {
  .CodeMirror-cursor {
    border-left: 4px solid black;
  }
}

div.output_wrapper {
  /* this position must be relative to enable descendents to be absolute within it */
  position: relative;

  display: -webkit-box;

  display: -moz-box;
  -moz-box-orient: vertical;
  -moz-box-align: stretch;

  box-orient: vertical;
  box-align: stretch;
  /* Modern browsers */
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  align-items: stretch;
  z-index: 1;
}
/* class for the output area when it should be height-limited */
div.output_scroll {
  /* ideally, this would be max-height, but FF barfs all over that */
  height: 24em;
  /* FF needs this *and the wrapper* to specify full width, or it will shrinkwrap */
  width: 100%;
  overflow: auto;
  border-radius: 2px;
  -webkit-box-shadow: inset 0 2px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.8);
  box-shadow: inset 0 2px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.8);
  display: block;
}
/* output div while it is collapsed */
div.output_collapsed {
  margin: 0px;

  display: -webkit-box;

div.out_prompt_overlay:hover {

}
div.output_prompt {

/* This class is the outer container of all output sections. */
div.output_area {

/* This class is for the output subarea inside the output_area and after
   the prompt div. */
div.output_subarea {
  overflow-x: auto;
  padding: 0.4em;
  /* Old browsers */
  -webkit-box-flex: 1;
  -moz-box-flex: 1;
  box-flex: 1;
  /* Modern browsers */

}
div.output_scroll div.output_subarea {

}
/* The rest of the output_* classes are for special styling of the different
   output types */
/* all text output has this class: */
div.output_text {
  text-align: left;
  color: #000;
  /* This has to match that of the the CodeMirror class line-height below */
  line-height: 1.21429em;
}
/* stdout/stderr are 'text' as well as 'stream', but execute_result/error are *not* streams */
div.output_stderr {
  background: #fdd;
  /* very light red background for stderr */
}
div.output_latex {

}
/* Empty output_javascript divs should have no height */

}
input.raw_input:focus {

<h1 id="Stu's-Data-Science-Blog">Stu's Data Science Blog<a class="anchor-link" href="#Stu's-Data-Science-Blog">¶</a></h1><h2 id="First-post.">First post.<a class="anchor-link" href="#First-post.">¶</a></h2><p>It is a little over a quarter of a century since I sat my last undergrad exam and close to two decades since I graduated from my PhD.  Since then I have spent my time in research institutions and universities in Australia, the US and Europe building skills and capabilities in developimng innovations in health, ageing and disability.</p>
<p>You can find a <a href="http://bit.ly/StuSmith2454">link to my research portfolio here</a></p>
<p>Today, a new career journey begins and I am once again enrolling as a student, this time in a postgrad diploma in <font color=blue>Data Science</font> at the University of New South Wales. The plan is to work my way through to a Masters of Data Science.</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="UNSW_acceptance.png"></p>
<p>To celebrate the occassion I'm writing my first blog post (this one) to track my experiences as I navigate my way through this exciting adventure. What better way to do so than by creating the blog in <a href="http://jupyter.org">jupyter</a>, a tool that I've just started learning and one that seems to be a standard part of the data scientist's toolkit. Why have I never used this great platform before I do not know. Too much of a <a href="http://mathworks.com">Matlab</a> fanboy I guess.</p>
<p>(Until I get the hang of formatting in markdown, these posts may appear visually uninspiring. Let's hope I pick up some tricks along the way.)</p>
<p>So, why am I picking up a new set of competencies?  Let's just say that after my most recent role in university-land was made redundant at the end of 2018, trying to find continued employment in the university sector or in the commercial world has proven challenging. This is especially the case as my family and I live in regional Australia, where there is only one university campus (from which I was made redundant), and we have no desire to up stumps and move on yet again trying to find employment in yet another short term contract.</p>
<p>We especially have no desire to return to living in a major metro like Sydney or Melbourne. Unfortunately for us, most roles I've seen advertised, and for which I would be competitive, are based in the big cities. I've a whole other point of view/rant about how I think this is particularly shortsighted on the part of employers. Another topic of conversation I'll take up at some point, perhaps in a separate blog, is also the issue of <a href="https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-12-02/ageism-rampant-discrimination-problem-in-the-workplace/10550704">ageism in exployment</a> in this country.</p>
<p>Interestingly, the commercial world appears to be unreasonably skeptical about the value that someone who has spent most of their career in research can bring. This is possibly well justified in many/most cases however, as I have  spent decades trying to understand the world from the perspective of industry, and have explored where ever possible translation of research, the biased attitudes I've encountered when looking for roles in industry is more than a little frustrating.</p>
<p>So, rather than continue to spiral into self doubt and depression ( unfortunately all too common for we "older" folk who find ourselves unexpectedly without employment ), I've decided to pivot into a career path where I suspect/hope that there will be a need for my skills. According to <a href="https://insidebigdata.com/2018/12/27/data-scientist-shortage-huge-heres-beat/">article such as this</a> and others I have been reading, it seems that there is a real demand for people who posses skills in data: its generation, storage, maintenance, manipulation, interpretation and visualisation. Hey, that sounds like the kinds of skills possessed by researchers so surely there's an opportunity for me here too.</p>
<p>So, I'll now fiddle about a bit and see if I can get this notebook converted into html and uploaded on github pages. Thanks to the folks at <a href="https://www.dataquest.io/blog/how-to-setup-a-data-science-blog/">dataquest.io</a> for an easy to follow explanation of how to do this.</p>
<p>Stu</p>
